As of 00:00 on March 3,600 new cases of coronavirus infection had been confirmed in South Korea, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 4812, the death rate to 28 and the cure rate to 34.

So far, in addition to confirmed cases, 121039 people have been tested for the virus in South Korea, 15,660 more in 24 hours, 85,484 of whom have tested negative, the remaining 35,555 results are not yet available.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Source: Korea Central Epidemic Prevention Countermeasures Department

In South Korea, more than 1,000 new cases of pneumonia were confirmed on the 26th, closing in on 5,000 in just six days. Currently, nearly 90% (89%) of confirmed cases in South Korea are concentrated in the neighboring regions of Taegu and Gyeongbuk, with two major infectious sites respectively: the New World Taegu Church and gyeongbuk-do County Dannan Hospital.

As of 0000 hours on February 2, a total of 2,418 cases (57.4%) had been confirmed with new world church-related cases in Taegu. As of 00:00 on the 3rd, there were 3600 confirmed cases in Daegu, 685 in Gyeongbuk, 519 and 61 new cases respectively, and 98,94 and 90 cases in Seoul, Gyeonggi Province and Busan.

The deaths were also mostly in Taegu and Qingbei, mostly in people over 60. At present, hospital beds in Taegu are in serious shortage. As of 9:00 am on the 1st, 2,569 cases had been confirmed in Taegu, of which only 898(35%) were hospitalized, the central daily reported Tuesday.

In recent days, there have been a number of deaths in Taegu during home quarantine. In response, Daegu Disaster Headquarters decided to open a 24-hour hotline, arrange for specialized doctors to be admitted to the hospital to track the management of patients and ensure the supply of needed drugs.

President Moon jae-in visited doctors and patients at the National Army Hospital in Daejeon on the same day and heard a report on the disease, Yonhap reported Tuesday. He stressed that transparent disclosure of information about the epidemic, speed up the detection and diagnosis of the virus, improve the efficiency of anti-epidemic.

It was only six days after Moon's visit to Taegu last month. At present, the Chinese military hospital admitted from Daegu City and North Gyeongsang Province into the 34 confirmed patients, the operation of "drive-in" virus detection stations. Moon inspected the drive-in test on site and asked other local self-government groups to follow suit.

South Korea's response to infectious diseases has improved significantly compared with the spread of the Middle East Respiratory Syndrome (MERS) epidemic in 2015, eliminating problems such as large numbers of health care workers being infected, Moon said. Moon also said he was deeply grateful for the 1,400 medical personnel sent by the military to the epidemic site, a quarter of the total number of military medical personnel, and urged them to do their utmost to safeguard the health and safety of the nation.

Moon said the rapid test developed by the Military Medical Research Institute, which has applied for approval from the Food and Drug Safety Administration, could reduce the time it takes to detect the new coronavirus from six hours to 20 minutes. If it can be approved for clinical application, it will greatly improve the speed of new coronavirus detection.
